'''''Driving Out a Devil''''' ({{lang-de|Er treibt den Teufel aus}}) is an early [[One-act play|one-act]] [[farce]] by the [[Twentieth-century theatre|20th-century]] German dramatist [[Bertolt Brecht]].<ref>Brecht (1994). The play's title is sometimes translated as ''He's Driving Out a Devil''; see Hayman (1983, 50).</ref> It was written in [[prose]], probably in [[1919 in literature#New drama|1919]], and was first published in volume 13 of Brecht's ''St<U+00FC>cke''.<ref>Thomson and Sacks (1994, xvii) and Willett (1967, 27).</ref> The play charts the attempts of a self-confident and manipulative [[Bavaria]]n [[peasant]] boy to outwit the vigilant parents of a girl of his village.<ref>Hayman (1983, 50-51).</ref> Ronald Hayman suggests that this play dramatises most clearly Brecht's own ability to influence people.<ref>Hayman writes that the play shows us "the way Brecht imposed his will on both women and men" (1983, 50).</ref>

